AGI -&nbsp;The meeting with the prisoners at the Giudecca, the visit to the Pavilion of the Holy See set up inside the prison for the Biennale, the gathering of young people in front of the Basilica della&nbsp; Madonna della Salute and the solemn celebration of the Mass in St Mark's Square. It 'was a very intense morning for Pope Francis welcomed in Venice with the usual enthusiasm of citizenship.&nbsp;Attered at 7.55 in the inner square of the house of recruitment of the island of Giudecca, the Pontiff, sitting in a wheelchair, greeted the present and received the welcome of the Patriarch of Venice, H.E. Mons. Francesco Moraglia, of the Minister of Justice Carlo Nordio, of the Provveditore Rosella Santoro, of the Director of the structure, Mariagrazia Felicita Bregoli and of the Commander of the Penitentiary Police, Lara Boco. In the inner courtyard of the House of Reclusion, the Pope met the detainees, in the presence of the administrative staff, the police officers and some volunteers.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>" Prison is a tough reality"</h2>
"The prison is a harsh reality, and problems such as overcrowding, lack of structures and resources, episodes of violence, generate you so much suffering," said Pope Francis meeting the prisoners.&nbsp; "No one removes dignity to a person, no one", he added, "it is fundamental that the prison system also offers to prisoners and held instruments and spaces of human, spiritual, cultural and professional growth, creating the reinstatement. Do not isolate dignity, but give new possibilities."
"I wanted to meet you at the beginning of my visit to Venice to tell you that you have a special place in my heart," he added, "I would like to live this moment not so much as an 'official visit' of the Pope, as well as a meeting where, by God's grace, we give each other time, prayer, closeness and fraternal affection. Today we're all going to get richer from this courtyard, the richest I will be, and the good we'll trade will be precious."
&nbsp;
After leaving the female penitentiary the Pope went to the adjacent Church of La Maddalena where he met with the artists who gave life to the Vatican Pavilion of the Biennale:&nbsp; "From here - he said - I would send to all this message: the world needs artists. It shows the multitude of people of every age who attend places and art events." "I confess that next to you I don't feel like a stranger: I feel at home. And I think that in reality this applies to every human being, because, to all intents and purposes, art is the statute of a city that disobeys the regime of violence and discrimination to create forms of human belonging capable of recognizing, including, protecting, embracing all. Everyone, starting with the last," he added.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"The refuge cities are a biblical institution, already mentioned in the deuteronomic code, destined to prevent the spread of innocent blood and to moderate the blind desire for revenge, to ensure the protection of human rights and to seek forms of reconciliation," he continued, "It would be important if the various artistic practices could be constituted everywhere as a kind of refugee city, collaborating to free the world from senseless and now emptied antinomy, but they seek There's selfishness that makes us work as solitary islands rather than as collaborative archipelagos. I implore you, friends artists, imagine cities that still do not exist on the map: cities where no human being is considered a stranger. That's why when we say foreigners everywhere, we're proposing brothers everywhere."
&nbsp;
<h2>Papa to young people, for God you are children and not a digital profile></h2>
Once on the feast of the basilica of Santa Maria della Salute in Venice, the Pope then met the young people of the dioceses of Triveneto.&nbsp;<span>"For God you are not a digital profile, but a son, you have a Father in the heavens and therefore you are the son of the sky - said the Pontiff -.&nbsp;</span> The risk is to leave everything to improvisation: Please, if I go to Mass when I want, I do good if I feel it. This does not give results: you must persevere, day after day. And do it together. Together: the DIY in great things does not work. For this I say to you: do not isolate yourselves, seek others, experience God together, follow group paths without tiring. You could say: 'But around me they're all on their own with their mobile phones attached to social media and video games.' And you without fear go against the current: take life in your hands, put yourself in play; turn off TV and open the Gospel; leave your mobile phone and meet people."
"We live immersed in products made by man, which make us miss the amazement for the beauty that surrounds us, yet the creation invites us to be in our turn creators of beauty, to do something that before was not there - the Pope said again -. Don't forget it, be beauty makers, do something that wasn't there before. It's good. When you're married and have a son, you've done something that wasn't there before. Think of the children you will have. Guys, don't be professionals to type compulsive, but novelty makers."
&nbsp;
<h2>Papa: young people are like Venice, beautiful and delicate </h2>
"God knows that, besides being beautiful, we are fragile, and the two things go together: a little like Venice, which is splendid and delicate at the same time - the Pope said -. Just Venice tells us that only rhymes with constancy go far. Of course, regularity is needed to row. but the constancy rewards, even if it costs fatigue. So, guys, this is getting up, letting yourself be taken by God to walk together."
&nbsp;
<h2> Mass in St Mark's Square
After crossing an electric car the bridge of boats thrown on the basin that divides Santa Maria della Salute from Piazza San Marco,&nbsp;Papa&nbsp;Francesco began the celebration of Mass, the last act of his visit to Venice. Francesco was welcomed at the entrance of the square by the President of the Veneto Region, Luca Zaia, the Prefect of Venice, Darco Pellos, and the mayor of the city, Luigi Brugnaro.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Venice is a symbol of inclusion, art and beauty accessible to all and the care of the common house," said the Pontiff in the homily pronounced in front of about 10,000 faithful. "Dear brothers and sisters, this is the fruit we are called to bring into our lives, in our relations, in the places we frequent every day, in our society," he explained. If today we look at this city of Venice, we admire its enchanting beauty, but we are also concerned about the many problems that threaten it: climate change, which has an impact on the waters of the lagoon and on the territory; the fragility of buildings, cultural goods, but also that of people; the difficulty of creating an environment that is man-made through adequate management of tourism; and also all that these realities are likely to generate in terms of social relationships, individualism and loneliness." "Venice, which has always been a place of encounter and cultural exchange, is called to be a sign of beauty accessible to all, starting from the last, a sign of fraternity and care for our common home," he added, "Resting united to Christ we can bear the fruits of the Gospel within the reality we live: fruits of justice and peace, fruits of solidarity and mutual care; attention choices for safeguarding the environmental heritage but also of the human heritage: We need our Christian communities, our neighborhoods, cities, to become hospitable, welcoming, inclusive places. "Venice is one with the waters on which it rises, and without the care and safeguarding of this natural scenery could even cease to exist. This is also our life: we, too, always immersed in the springs of God's love, have been regenerated into Baptism, are reborn to new life by the water and the Holy Spirit and inserted in Christ as the branches in the vine", concluded Pope Francis.
&nbsp;
At the end of the Mass, the Patriarch of Venice, Francesco Moraglia addressed to the &nbsp;Papa&nbsp; a greeting address. "Venice is a beautiful city, fragile, unique and, ever since, a bridge between the East and the West, a crossroads of peoples, cultures and different faiths", he said, "For this reason, in Venice, the great themes of your encyclicals - Brothers all and Laudato si' - find punctual feedback: the respect and care of creation and of the person, beginning with the high good of life that always needs to be respected and loved, especially when it is fragile and asks to be welcomed." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
